TY  - JOUR
T1  - Pollution and Performance: Do Investors Make Worse Trades on Hazy Days?
AU  - Huang, Jiekun
AU  - Xu, Nianhang
AU  - Yu, Honghai
Y1  - 2020/03/16
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2020/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3402
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3402
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 4455
EP  - 4476
VL  - 66
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper examines the relation between air pollution and individual investors? trading behavior and performance. Using unique data on stock trades by 87,504 individuals from 34 cities in China, we find a negative relation between air pollution and trade performance. This result is obtained after controlling for investor-year fixed effects and date fixed effects, as well as local weather conditions. More strikingly, abnormal trade performance decreases monotonically with the levels indicating the severity of air pollution. Furthermore, we find evidence suggesting that air pollution makes investors more susceptible to the disposition effect and attention-driven buying behavior. Overall, the results highlight a hitherto-unexplored cost that ambient air pollution imposes on stock market investors.This paper was accepted by Tylor Shumway, finance.
AB  - This paper examines the relation between air pollution and individual investors? trading behavior and performance. Using unique data on stock trades by 87,504 individuals from 34 cities in China, we find a negative relation between air pollution and trade performance. This result is obtained after controlling for investor-year fixed effects and date fixed effects, as well as local weather conditions. More strikingly, abnormal trade performance decreases monotonically with the levels indicating the severity of air pollution. Furthermore, we find evidence suggesting that air pollution makes investors more susceptible to the disposition effect and attention-driven buying behavior. Overall, the results highlight a hitherto-unexplored cost that ambient air pollution imposes on stock market investors.This paper was accepted by Tylor Shumway, finance.
