T1  - The Political Economy of Labor Employment Decisions: Evidence from China
AU  - Gu, Zhaoyang
AU  - Tang, Song
AU  - Wu, Donghui
Y1  - 2020/01/23
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2020/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3345
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3345
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 4703
EP  - 4725
VL  - 66
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In China?s transitional economy, one of the major objectives of the government is to maintain social stability. We hypothesize that, through state ownership and appointment of executives, Chinese government officials can influence firms? labor employment decisions by limiting layoffs when firms? sales decline. Consistent with this hypothesis, we find that state-owned enterprises (SOEs) have stickier labor costs than non-SOEs, and the presence of politically connected managers makes labor costs even stickier in SOEs while having little effect in non-SOEs. Such effects are stronger in regions with weak market institutions and during time periods when government officials are to be promoted. We also show that the government reciprocates SOEs? sticky labor policies with subsequent subsidies.This paper was accepted by Suraj Srinivasan, accounting.
AB  - In China?s transitional economy, one of the major objectives of the government is to maintain social stability. We hypothesize that, through state ownership and appointment of executives, Chinese government officials can influence firms? labor employment decisions by limiting layoffs when firms? sales decline. Consistent with this hypothesis, we find that state-owned enterprises (SOEs) have stickier labor costs than non-SOEs, and the presence of politically connected managers makes labor costs even stickier in SOEs while having little effect in non-SOEs. Such effects are stronger in regions with weak market institutions and during time periods when government officials are to be promoted. We also show that the government reciprocates SOEs? sticky labor policies with subsequent subsidies.This paper was accepted by Suraj Srinivasan, accounting.
